primaryData.textualContent: Security firms are companies where equities, bonds, and derivatives are traded within an organized exchange, or over-the-counter. The professional participants ranging from brokers, dealers, market makers, investment managers, and speculators are used to perform and manage a set of trading activities in order to respond to market players needs and gain capital. These trading activities are various by nature and can be mainly classified as follows: position trading, pure and risk arbitrage, program trading, stock blockage, and electronic blockage. The existence of a well-structured security market allows capital attraction, investment enhancement, and price determination, which ensures market equilibrium between supply and demand. In this report, we will focus on position trading and pure arbitrage by assessing their benefits and possible drawbacks. Position trading, also known as long-term trading or trend trading, refers to having a position on an asset and speculating on its major trend that may last for months or years. In fact, long-term market prices of a security tend to reflect its own real value and performance. However, the small fluctuations caused by transaction cost in the micro-market-structure and temporary shock of the market are generally recovered from and the stock price tends to return to its main trend. Hence, position trading usually puts great emphasis on fundamental analysis, trying to identify the general asset trend and its long-term performance, despite technical analysis possibly being a better choice in a booming market. Therefore, one of the main advantages of position trading is the lower number of transactions, which induces less costs as this strategy captures larger changes in value, thus, fewer trading orders are required. Consequently, less maintenance and monitoring of the portfolio is needed, which again, contributes to reduced costs in terms of salary and time, since small fluctuations and minor variations of market conditions are neglected. By holding a large number of shares, security firms may participate in strategic decisions of companies and motivate the managers to act in favour of position traders to manipulate the long-term prices since, in many countries, using inside information in placing trading positions is illegal. In conclusion, trading activities performed by security firms are very sensitive and require a high level of proficiency and expertise to reduce risk and achieve return goals. Adopting long-term trading strategies could always be beneficial as the general trend of any asset is mostly upward due to global economic expansion. However, security firms must be aware of the amount of risk associated with their positions and should keenly develop effective hedging strategies to avoid large market fluctuations resulting from any specific event. In addition, investors should operate in diversified portfolios and pick assets from various industries and classes after conducting fundamental and technical analysis to mitigate risk and maximize growth opportunities. As for pure arbitrage, security firms may have few opportunities to make some return in a risk-free environment. However, companies must not rely on these because of their limited opportunities and tight profit margins. Indeed, due to the spread of technology and new financial regulations that support economies of scales and the concept of asymmetric information in the market, arbitrage is becoming relatively less advantageous. In this case, firms are advised to rationally perform arbitrage activities taking into consideration their transactions costs and taxes.
